{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486791"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"176"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/176"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.06,0.03,0.48,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"176"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81009"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/176"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"176"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66341"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"176"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81009"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of left shoulder pain and stiffness. The pain is worse at night and all shoulder movements are restricted. He is right-handed and can no longer play bowls due to these symptoms. There is no history of trauma. He does not have pain in any other joints. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. His medications include metformin and amlodipine. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is marked reduction in both active and passive range of motion of the left shoulder. The \u0027empty can\u0027 test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most strongly associated with this patient\u0027s probable diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repetitive overhead activity","Symptoms in the side of the dominant hand","Male gender","History of diabetes mellitus","Age over 70"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of adhesive capsulitis (frozen shoulder), characterised by gradual onset of shoulder pain and stiffness affecting both active and passive range of motion. The negative empty can test helps rule out rotator cuff pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistory of diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E has the strongest association with adhesive capsulitis, with up to 20% of diabetic patients experiencing an episode during their lifetime. The exact mechanism is not fully understood but may relate to glycosylation of collagen in the joint capsule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepetitive overhead activity\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with rotator cuff pathology and superior labrum anterior to posterior (SLAP) tears, rather than adhesive capsulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymptoms in the side of the dominant hand\u003C/strong\u003E is actually contrary to the typical presentation - adhesive capsulitis more commonly affects the non-dominant arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMale gender\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor; adhesive capsulitis is actually more common in women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge over 70\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with adhesive capsulitis, which most commonly affects people aged 40-60 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther conditions associated with adhesive capsulitis include thyroid disease, cardiovascular disease, and prolonged immobilisation. The condition typically progresses through painful, frozen, and thawing phases over 18-24 months, though this duration can be longer in diabetic patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Up to 20% of patients with diabetes mellitus may experience an episode of adhesive capsulitis.","Adhesive capsulitis typically presents with gradual onset shoulder pain and stiffness affecting both active and passive range of motion.","Women aged 40-60 years are most commonly affected by adhesive capsulitis, typically in the non-dominant arm."],"references":["Manske R, Prohaska D. Diagnosis and management of adhesive capsulitis. Curr Rev Musculoskelet Med. 2008; 1(3-4):180-189.","Le H, Lee S, Nazarian A, Rodriguez E. Adhesive capsulitis of the shoulder: review of pathophysiology and current clinical treatments. Shoulder Elbow. 2017; 9(2):75-84.","Blom A, Warwick D, Whitehouse M, editors. Apley \u0026 Solomon\u0027s System of Orthopaedics and Trauma. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66341"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"176"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66341"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-24T21:20:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T21:20:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"176"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81009"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"at